  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "I want to go and work abroad, dont have much of a professional degree like engineering, I have done b.a. and gniit, is there a scope. my age is 25?",
  "response": "Absolutely, there's potential for you to work abroad even if you don't have a professional degree like engineering. Here are some pathways you might consider:\n\n1. **Teaching English Abroad**: Many countries have a high demand for English teachers. Programs such as TEFL (Teaching English as a Foreign Language) or TESOL (Teaching English to Speakers of Other Languages) certifications can enhance your qualifications.\n\n2. **Hospitality and Tourism**: These sectors often have roles that require minimal formal education, such as positions in hotels, restaurants, and tourist attractions.\n\n3. **Remote Work and Freelancing**: Explore online platforms where you can offer services like writing, graphic design, and digital marketing. You can work remotely from anywhere in the world.\n\n4. **Volunteering Programs**: Some international volunteer organizations offer room and board in exchange for work, which can also provide valuable experience and potential employment opportunities.\n\n5. **Au Pair Programs**: Working as an au pair can be a great way to live abroad while earning a stipend and gaining cultural experience.\n\n6. **Customer Service Jobs**: Many global companies have customer service positions in different countries, which may not require specialized degrees.\n\n7. **Internships and Entry-level Jobs**: Look for internships or entry-level positions in industries that interest you. Often, international companies value soft skills and cultural fit alongside formal qualifications.\n\nTo maximize your chances:\n- **Build a compelling resume**: Highlight any relevant experience and skills.\n- **Learn the language**: Knowing the language of the destination country can be a huge asset.\n- **Network**: Connect with people working abroad in your desired sector.\n- **Research Visa Requirements**: Understand what types of visas you might be eligible for in different countries.\n\nRemember, many employers value practical experience and enthusiasm, so don't be discouraged by the lack of a specialized degree.",
